Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He hated it especially because he was responsible for waking up everyone else in his platoon. Quietly, he got up from his cot, put on his combat suit, threw his body armor over it, and took his things out of the locker, being careful with a certain small box. He shouldered his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Everything he needed was attached to it, like his breathing apparatus or his special goggles. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, mud and ice crackled under his boots.
He pulled a lighter from one jacket pocket and a cigarette from the other. He lit it and took a short puff before opening the door a little. In the last week, he had to come up with quite a few ideas to wake up the men and women under his command. He no longer used the preset alarm, because it usually didn't work and only a faint noise came out of the speakers.
"Are you waking them?" Cohren turned around and saw train conductor Nemic approaching him.
"Yes," answered Cohren.
"What are you going to try this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and a few others came toward him already fully dressed.
"Good morning," said Craith.
"What did you wake up from?" asked Cohren.
"Well, first of all, we didn't feel like waiting for whatever idea you'd come up with today again. And secondly, the assault troops, who are supposed to get up first, get to choose their morning ration," replied one of the men, Ravik. "And you know how bad the food can be."
"Good point, corporal," said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a switch. A loud, shrill alarm echoed through the barracks. Inside, he heard muffled cursing and people running around in a panic.
"Come on, Valturi," said Nemic. "One would think they'd have learned by now to wake up at the same time as you."
"Well, my guys from the training camp have learned it," replied Cohren, pointing at Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "However, the platoon and squad leaders also know that they have to get up before their units."
Seconds later, the rest of the company came out. They had everything they needed, from personal belongings to the necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, others more annoyed.
"Good morning," said Cohren in a good mood.
"With all due respect, sir, why do you have to wake us up like this?" asked a squad leader from the assault troops.
"Because the regular alarms are crap and because Daybreak doesn't oversleep," said Cohren.
"Pack up all your personal belongings," Cohren continued. As a lieutenant colonel and executive officer of the company, he was responsible for overseeing and supporting them along with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be coming back here. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack your daily rations."
The members of the Exodus Company quickly dispersed. They were part of the Second Assault Division, Second Army. Before they were combined, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was split, and that was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings about his promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Cohren and Nemic, the conductor of the first train, walked side by side in the glow of the many generator-powered lamps of the forward operating base. Most had tinted red glass to avoid detection by enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild-Weasel attacks from the air and on the ground to combat them.
"A new day and a new mission for the Hellhounds," said Nemic with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"An advanced operating base outside Ianlos. We will support the ground attack," answered Cohren and took a drag on his cigarette. He gave Craith partial credit for getting him started on smoking, but a year in the field changed a man, so he said nothing.
"Shit. It's getting worse at the front," muttered Nemic. "All the news says: 'Support the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan Front.' How about some help for the Howland Front?"
"Amen, brother," said Cohren and flicked the remains of his cigarette into the mud. "At least we're leaving with the first armed train and don't have to run. Captain Shaw should already be there."
"Shaw made it clear we have a ride?" Nemic asked, a bit surprised.
"True. He's honestly not as bad as I thought. Not particularly friendly, but you can put up with him."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone and put on his backpack. "All units of the Exodus Company will gather at West Yard when they're ready. We'll depart with the first armed train at 0500."
In seconds, he received responses from the squad leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they all came here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren felt like he had known them for ages, even though it had been at most two years. They were squad leaders, although Craith had been leading the second train for a week, after its previous leader had been discharged for medical reasons following a shot from a Daybreak sniper.
On their way to the yard, Cohren and Nemic spotted a group of about eight Kronos battle tanks and four armored personnel carriers. Their crews were walking around and making sure their machines were combat-ready. Cohren quickly recognized Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking to the commander of the armed train. As they approached, Shaw looked over at them and came toward them, as always with an expressionless face.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said, noting that Cohren was slower as he looked at Cohren's pistol holster and then looked up again. "The company is ready, I assume?"
